,"header":"Twin sons: one to Boston missions","body":"John Worthington and Henry Brown Hooker were born the same day — August 31, 1802 — and their lives diverged completely: John moved to Chicago in 1836 among the city's earliest New England settlers, while Henry graduated Middlebury College, entered the ministry, and became Secretary of Missions at Boston."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Two of five children died in Chicago","body":"John Worthington Hooker moved to Chicago in 1836 and died there in 1866; his sister Julia Ann married a Rutland lawyer and also died in Chicago in 1842. Two of Thomas Hooker's five children ended their days in the city that barely existed when they were born."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"slug":"thomas-hooker-1770"},"I01188":{"id":"I01188","is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"former_ids":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Brown Hooker","first_name":"Sarah","middle_name":"Brown","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1779,"city":"Pittsfield","county":"Berkshire","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1832,"month":1,"day":11,"city":"Rutland","county":"Rutland","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00530","date_year":1796,"end_type":"death","end_year":1832,"children_ids":["H01416","H01417","H01418","H01419","H01420"]}],"career":[],"education":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Probably daughter of a Revolutionary War martyr","body":"Sarah Brown's father, Colonel John Brown of Pittsfield Massachusetts named in the Hooker genealogy, is almost certainly the Revolutionary War officer killed at the Battle of Stone Arabia, New York, on October 19, 1780 — when Sarah was barely a year old. She married Thomas Hooker in 1796 and died at Rutland, Vermont, in 1832, four years before her husband."}],"naming_inspiration":[],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM553"},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"sources":[{"short":"FindAGrave #43726558 + EH 1909 #530"}],"research_sources":[],"slug":"sarah-hooker-1779"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM560","name":"Hillside Cemetery","city":"Whitewater","county":"Walworth","state":"Wisconsin","country":"United States","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/88154/hillside-cemetery","hooker_connections":["H02765","I01193","H02767","H04371","H04372","I01199","H04374","I01200","H04376","H05273","H05274","H05275","H05276","H05279","H05280","H05281","I01194","I01209","H04375"],"notes":"Whitewater, Walworth County WI. FGA #88154. Contains Thomas Hooker Goodhue Sr., Josiah Goodhue, and many Goodhue-branch descendants."},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}